<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-677-602  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 677 602.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Expert  June 1990 v5 n3 p8(8).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Planning for space telerobotics: the remote mission specialist.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rokey, Mark; Grenander, Sven.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Study is underway at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL) onplanning problems.andP;  The goals of the researchers are to makecommand generation for spacecraft more automatic and to automatecompletely plan generation, in an effort to place a controllingintelligence on board a spacecraft.andP;  As part of the effort to bulda manned space station, Congress requires the inclusion ofautomation and robotics.andP;  JPL researchers are working ondeveloping needed technologies for space-based robotics and ontechnologies that enable robots to perform structural assembly andrepair operations for spacecraft in orbit.andP;  One component is aplanning and reasoning subsystem called TIPS(Telerobot InteractivePlanning System).andP;  TIPS performs in an autonomous fashion or as aninterface between the robotic system and human operators.andP;  The RMStask planner is contained in TIPS.andP;  RMS works in two planningstages.andP;  The first stage decides what tasks to do and the secondstage decides how to do those tasks.andP;  Space-based robots thatservice equipment must be adaptable and fast, and must have ahigh-level planner that supports options for a human operator touse if necessary.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Jet Propulsion Laboratory (research).andO;Topic:     RobotsSpace ExplorationResearch and Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Telerobot interactive planning system. (chart)Computer-generated example action-unit network. (chart)Computer-generated simulator view of robot arms. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>